    <h1 id="lesson-2"><b> Lesson 2: Creating a Structured Document With HTML </b>    </h1>
 </div>
 <div class="concept" id="lesson-2-1">
      <div class="concept-title">
 <h2><b>Important Concepts</b></h2>
 </div>
 
 <div class="concept-description">
 <p> HTML and CSS are both languages. HTML controls the structure of a webpage. CSS controls the style of a page. When programmers talk about the "DOM" or Document Object Model, they are talking about the tree-like structure of a page. HTML consists of boxes. All of your content will be inside of a box. We use the div tag to seperate our boxes.
 </p>
 </div>
 </div>
    <div class="concept" id="lesson-2-2">
      <div class="concept-title">
  <h2><b> Tree-Like Structure</b></h2>
    </div>
     <div class="concept-description">
    <p>HTML is made up of a tree like structure or a branching structure consisting of opening and closing tags. For example you have a div tag which seperates all of your boxes that contain your content. Then you have your header and p (paragraph) tag branching off of your div tag. Within your header tag you have   your text. Within your p tag you have your text, img (image) tag, and so on.
     </p>
    </div>
    </div>
    
